down-conversion tapes where you

00:03:37.030 --> 00:03:39.340
have your high-definition media.

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:44.370
Because you don't have a D5 deck
or an HD deck in your edit suite,

00:03:44.390 --> 00:03:47.390
you will have a facility
down-converted for you to a

00:03:47.390 --> 00:03:49.840
standard-definition NTSC cassette.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:54.640
And so in that process,
you take 2398 media,

00:03:54.670 --> 00:03:59.520
and you have to somehow
get it to 2997 NTSC.

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:02.460
And to do that,
you actually introduce something.

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:05.700
You have something called 3-2,
which is where you take

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:09.170
the fields of the video,
and you repeat them in a 3-2 pattern

00:04:09.170 --> 00:04:13.780
so that you add the six frames that
are missing between that 24 and 30.

00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:17.780
I'm going to use the 24
and 30 interchangeably here

00:04:17.780 --> 00:04:20.800
with the 2399 and 2997.

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:22.340
They're in essence the same thing.

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:27.200
So you have this 3-2 pull-down
that's added to your tapes for

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:30.340
the standard-definition workflow.

00:04:30.340 --> 00:04:32.330
And then they basically tape.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:38.960
You take those standard-definition
tapes and either work in 2997 or remove

00:04:38.960 --> 00:04:42.820
the 3-2 and work in a 2398 workflow.

00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:46.540
And that's a couple of steps
in a workflow right there.

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:50.300
You have EDLs, edit decision lists.

00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:52.930
We'll talk a little bit
more about that shortly.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:58.300
But you have to somehow get the
information from your offline cut,

00:04:58.450 --> 00:05:01.820
what you've basically been
editing for four or five months,

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:05.750
until your feature is finished,
to the online room.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:08.260
The online room is where
you do your mastering,

00:05:08.260 --> 00:05:12.150
where you take that standard-definition
project and make it into a

00:05:12.150 --> 00:05:16.580
high-definition finished master
that you can air or broadcast,

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:20.500
or you can take out to film,
whatever your project entails.

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:24.110
And then another thing about
standard-definition down conversions is

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:26.440
that you have a change in aspect ratio.

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:30.840
You have your high-definition
tapes are -- they're widescreen.

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:31.820
They're 16 by 9.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:35.920
Yet when you do a down conversion
to a standard-definition tape,

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:39.450
you're working in 4 by 3,
normal television size.

00:05:39.660 --> 00:05:43.780
And you can either work
it a couple of ways.

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:47.740
You can do a squeezed standard-definition
tape where you have -- if you

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:51.320
look at it on a normal monitor,
people are tall and skinny,

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:53.680
and then they get unsqueezed
to do a widescreen.

00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:57.610
Or you have a center extraction
where you only take the center

00:05:57.630 --> 00:05:59.950
information and cut off the sides.

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:01.160
Or you can do a letterbox extraction.

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:04.770
You can do a letterbox extraction where
you shrink everything down and you have

00:06:04.770 --> 00:06:07.000
the black on the top and the bottom.

00:06:07.050 --> 00:06:11.520
These particular methods
have ramifications for when

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:17.670
you go to your mastering,
which we'll talk about shortly.

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:24.920
So, one of the things in talking and
giving these seminars and giving,

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:28.680
you know, explaining the traditional
workflow for the 240th time,

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:34.170
something occurred to me,
is that traditional HD workflow is hard.

00:06:34.210 --> 00:06:36.190
It's unnecessarily so.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:41.160
The entire idea that you have,
that you work at a different time code

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:45.030
rate than what your master tapes are,
that you have to change

00:06:45.170 --> 00:06:48.970
this aspect ratio,
all these particular parts of the

00:06:49.130 --> 00:06:52.180
workflow make it unnecessarily hard.

00:06:52.180 --> 00:06:57.370
And so, I end up having people asking me,
why do we have to work with these 2997

00:06:57.370 --> 00:07:00.520
cassettes when our masters are 2398?

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:05.230
Why are we dealing with 4x3 when
it's actually 16x9 that we shot?

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:07.820
And so, Thank you.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.570
You then have the EDLs,
the Edit Decision List,

00:07:10.570 --> 00:07:13.520
that's basically 30-year-old technology.

00:07:13.520 --> 00:07:15.820
Ironically,
it's still something we use today,

00:07:15.820 --> 00:07:21.210
and a lot of facilities depend on it,
because it has been that kind

00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:26.780
of Rosetta Stone that we use to
talk between editing products.

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:30.250
But an EDL is just a text file.

00:07:30.250 --> 00:07:34.260
It's a text file that has timecode
values for your source tapes,

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:39.700
timecode values for your master tape,
and little descriptions,

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:40.780
but it's all text.

00:07:44.620 --> 00:07:46.560
Oh, actually, I can go.

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:49.150
They're pretty limiting
because they're text files.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:53.500
Depending on the format that you have,
you either have two levels of

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:55.780
video and four levels of audio.

00:07:55.780 --> 00:07:56.860
That's an example.

00:07:56.860 --> 00:07:59.480
Some have two levels of video,
two levels of audio.

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:04.290
The titles and effects, transitions,
they're only partially supported.

00:08:04.450 --> 00:08:08.660
You get a little note saying that you
have a dissolve there of a certain type,

00:08:08.790 --> 00:08:11.400
but you don't know if you
have an iris dissolve,

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:14.390
if you have a fade up
or something like that.

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:15.690
That's not actually in there.

00:08:15.700 --> 00:08:18.350
And in motion effects,
where you take your video,

00:08:18.350 --> 00:08:20.680
you blow it up slightly
or you move it around,

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:22.360
that's not supported at all.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:25.740
So,
if you're working on modern equipment,

00:08:25.740 --> 00:08:29.680
modern edit systems,
you have a lot more control.

00:08:29.860 --> 00:08:34.990
You take a Final Cut Pro project,
for example, you have 99 video tracks.

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:36.850
You have 99 audio tracks.

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:42.750
If you take a Final Cut Pro project from
one system and take it into another,

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:46.630
all of the special effects,
the transitions, the titles,

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:49.850
speed changes,
all of those things come across.

00:08:49.860 --> 00:08:53.650
And so, if you're working in a
Final Cut Pro environment

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:58.850
and you want to make an EDL,
you actually have to hold yourself back.

00:08:58.860 --> 00:08:59.860
You have to hold yourself back.

00:08:59.860 --> 00:09:03.860
And edit in a way so that
the EDL will work nicely,

00:09:03.860 --> 00:09:06.860
that it will play nice with
whatever system you end up

00:09:06.860 --> 00:09:06.860
going to for your online.

00:09:06.860 --> 00:09:13.200
So, basically,
you can do a lot of things with this.

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:16.780
We were there,
I kind of came to this little

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:22.810
conclusion that there should be a
better way to do high definition.

00:09:22.810 --> 00:09:26.000
And so,
with the help of the QuickTime team,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.760
the Final Cut Pro team,
and hardware support

00:09:28.760 --> 00:09:31.520
from AJA and Pinnacle,
we've come up with a different

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:33.710
way to do high definition.

00:09:34.940 --> 00:09:51.480
And I think it's actually
a better workflow.

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:51.600
And better for me means simple,
because I don't want it

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:51.600
to be a complicated thing.

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:51.600
So, with this particular
workflow is used now,

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:57.900
At Warner Brothers, and 20th Century Fox,
and where HD is really prevalent

00:09:57.920 --> 00:10:00.930
in the independent community,
we have several independent

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:04.210
filmmakers that are using it,
and Showtime is going to be doing

00:10:04.340 --> 00:10:08.620
three shows starting in about
two weeks for their next season,

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:10.760
using this particular system.

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:13.950
So before I go too much into
what the actual system is,

00:10:13.950 --> 00:10:16.560
I'll tell you a little bit
about the basics of HD,

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:21.430
and why this change,
this paradigm shift is so important.

00:10:21.740 --> 00:10:27.690
With HD, pretty much everybody knows the
reason why you want to work with HD is

00:10:27.750 --> 00:10:29.570
that you have great visual quality.

00:10:29.570 --> 00:10:35.160
If you have an NTSC signal,
you're working with 720x486

00:10:35.160 --> 00:10:37.120
lines of resolution.

00:10:37.150 --> 00:10:39.800
If you're talking DigiBeta,
it's 480 if you're DV.

00:10:40.800 --> 00:10:45.330
With that,
you can go up to a high-definition

00:10:45.390 --> 00:10:50.800
signal where you're 1920x1080.

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:54.410
So you have drastically more pixels
and lines of resolution to work with.

00:10:54.470 --> 00:10:56.190
And the picture is so much nicer.

00:10:56.240 --> 00:11:01.710
What you also have is that
NTSC is an interlaced format.

00:11:01.810 --> 00:11:07.550
And so it draws a single frame
with two fields of video that's

00:11:07.550 --> 00:11:10.670
clocked to our electrical.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:12.800
So we got a 60 hertz electrical.

00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:18.730
And so we have 60 fields that come
together to make the 30 frames of video,

00:11:18.730 --> 00:11:20.250
or 2997.

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:21.940
That's kind of an old thing.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:25.370
So you have these interlaced
fields that come together.

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:28.860
And so what ends up happening
is that you have the first field

00:11:29.010 --> 00:11:31.020
draw half of the information.

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:36.830
And then the second field comes in like a
zipper and completes the picture for you.

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:40.690
With high-definition,
if you're talking about 24 pixels...

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:46.910
...and you have a true whole image
from top to bottom drawn at once.

00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:50.240
So it's more filmic in that regard.

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:55.140
And so that's the whole
appeal of working in 24p HD.

00:11:55.400 --> 00:11:57.920
That quality comes at a price.

00:11:57.920 --> 00:11:59.980
The price is data rate.

00:12:00.140 --> 00:12:03.320
And so depending on what
kind of format you're doing,

00:12:03.390 --> 00:12:09.130
you're talking anywhere from 90 megabytes
a second to 160 megabytes a second.

00:12:09.140 --> 00:12:10.140
So that's the appeal
of working in 24p HD.

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:14.040
But that's a lot of data to
get in and off your drives.

00:12:14.060 --> 00:12:17.900
And so this is not the type of thing
that you can do off of a firewire.

00:12:18.040 --> 00:12:22.040
It's not the type of thing that you
can do off of a single IDE drive.

00:12:22.040 --> 00:12:26.040
So at our facilities,
to get a speed like this,

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:28.030
we use an XSERV RAID maxed out.

00:12:28.040 --> 00:12:31.950
14 drives RAIDed together
in a RAID 50 to get the data

00:12:31.950 --> 00:12:33.950
rate fast enough to handle HD.

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:39.040
And not only that,
you also have the fact that...

00:12:39.380 --> 00:12:44.100
The data, since the data rate is so high,
you use up a lot of hard

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:45.700
drive space very quickly.

00:12:45.820 --> 00:12:48.200
And so, you take a look at this
difference right here.

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:52.360
Here you have DV, it's rounded up,
but you have DV,

00:12:52.360 --> 00:12:55.360
which is a compressed SD signal.

00:12:55.740 --> 00:12:59.200
The native format as
it's recorded on tape.

00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:00.620
Then you have SD 10-bit.

00:13:00.820 --> 00:13:04.350
If you take a DigiBeta tape and
you do a 10-bit uncompressed,

00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:06.880
you're working at 27 megabytes a second.

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:10.740
So, when you do the jump to HD,
you see uncompressed

00:13:10.950 --> 00:13:13.670
HD actually jumps quite a bit.

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:16.560
You have 126 megabytes
a second for 1080p.

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:22.230
And then for 1080i, 2997,
you're talking 160 megabytes a second.

00:13:22.230 --> 00:13:25.750
So,
you're chowing through hard drive space.

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:29.440
And so,
uncompressed HD is not really very

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:33.340
useful or practical for offline editing.

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:38.150
Because if you're a traditional feature,
motion picture, in Hollywood,

00:13:38.150 --> 00:13:42.140
you'll shoot about 60 hours,
70 hours of footage.

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:46.440
And so, at HD,
uncompressed HD data rates.

00:13:46.910 --> 00:13:51.630
You're talking somewhere on the
lines of 60 to 70 terabytes of

00:13:52.180 --> 00:13:56.300
storage that you need for 5,
6 months while your editor and your

00:13:56.300 --> 00:14:00.840
director is whittling down that
60 hours to an hour and a half.

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:05.100
And so, that's not a practical
thing to keep track of.

00:14:05.180 --> 00:14:11.800
It's very expensive because you need
to buy XRARs or like large SCSI arrays.

00:14:12.020 --> 00:14:16.620
So, working in uncompressed
HD is not practical at all.

00:14:18.050 --> 00:14:21.010
So because of that,
the traditional workflow had

00:14:21.010 --> 00:14:23.090
this down conversion mentality.

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:27.460
Since working in uncompressed
HD isn't practical,

00:14:27.470 --> 00:14:30.900
and there was no other
solution available before,

00:14:31.030 --> 00:14:32.850
down conversions was the only way to go.

00:14:32.890 --> 00:14:37.140
But you have all the hang-ups
that come along with that

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:39.970
standard definition workflow.

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:45.440
At Technicolor, we were thinking that we
wanted to stay digital.

00:14:45.710 --> 00:14:47.460
We didn't want to go down to a Beta SP.

00:14:47.460 --> 00:14:49.600
We didn't want to go down to a DVCam.

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:54.990
We wanted to give them
QuickTime movies delivered on FireWire.

00:14:55.030 --> 00:14:59.540
And those QuickTime movies are
direct descendants from the HD.

00:14:59.540 --> 00:15:05.680
We'll take D5HD, HDCam,
and bring it in and transcode

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:11.840
it on the fly to an offline
format that the company requests.

00:15:11.900 --> 00:15:18.410
And that offline format can be PhotoJPG,
which is very good quality

00:15:18.410 --> 00:15:21.940
but a very low data rate,
very nice for offline editing,

00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:24.700
particularly if you have
a lot of hours of footage.

00:15:24.740 --> 00:15:33.720
We can go to DV and
we'll do it a 16 by 9 DV.

00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:33.720
We'll go DV50 or--

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:40.170
Since about two, three months,
we can go to DVC Pro HD with the

00:15:40.170 --> 00:15:42.420
new Final Cut Pro HD version.

00:15:42.420 --> 00:15:45.440
And so we'll talk a little bit
more about that and show why

00:15:45.440 --> 00:15:47.460
that's an interesting workflow.

00:15:49.030 --> 00:15:54.010
So with the Final Cut Pro HD media,
we are giving high

00:15:54.010 --> 00:15:56.380
quality QuickTime movies.

00:15:56.570 --> 00:16:00.990
The time code that you see in your
Final Cut Pro system corresponds

00:16:01.010 --> 00:16:02.600
exactly to the master tapes.

00:16:02.600 --> 00:16:07.620
And so there's no difference between
time codes that you're dealing with.

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:12.580
And so when you go do your
mastering of your movie,

00:16:12.580 --> 00:16:16.420
all the time codes line up and
it simplifies things there.

00:16:16.420 --> 00:16:20.060
You don't have to change the lists,
go through any kind of

00:16:20.060 --> 00:16:21.800
conversion processes.

00:16:22.300 --> 00:16:25.750
Like in Cinema Tools right now,
we have something where you can go

00:16:25.810 --> 00:16:28.440
from a 2997 list to a 2398 list.

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:29.540
You don't need to do any of that.

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:32.580
So the time code comes across exactly.

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:35.230
The data rate is low.

00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:39.370
And so it can be as low as 1 50th,
the original data rate.

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:41.880
That's in particular with the photo JPEG.

00:16:41.940 --> 00:16:45.840
And it preserves a 16 by 9 aspect ratio.

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:50.420
What's nice about that is that you see
everything that you have on the HD tape.

00:16:50.460 --> 00:16:54.090
You can see if there's... There is...

00:16:54.650 --> 00:17:13.150
A light stand in the shot on this side,
whereas if you do a 4x3 extraction,

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:13.150
you might have missed that.

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:13.150
You can time things so that they happen
properly when someone walks out of frame

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:13.150
that you know exactly when they leave,
whereas if you have a

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:13.150
4x3 center extraction,
they would seem to leave

00:17:13.150 --> 00:17:13.150
the frame far earlier.

00:17:14.320 --> 00:17:18.340
So, the first show that we did this with
was a Warner Brothers independent

00:17:18.340 --> 00:17:22.070
movie called Around the Bend,
which is coming out, I believe,

00:17:22.070 --> 00:17:22.550
in August.

