meaning transferring to high definition,

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:34.820
to HDD5.

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:41.710
We picked D5 because it's a 10-bit media.

00:17:42.810 --> 00:17:49.800
Then we captured it on the fly from
the D5 and we went to half HD res.

00:17:49.830 --> 00:17:54.160
And so the resolution that they
were working at was greater

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:55.300
than standard definition.

00:17:56.070 --> 00:17:58.130
It was 960x540.

00:17:58.340 --> 00:18:01.310
It was perfect 16x9.

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:05.240
The average data rate
was 2 megabytes a second.

00:18:05.410 --> 00:18:09.300
So we went from 126 megabytes to 2.

00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:15.530
And that two megabytes is less than DV,
by the way.

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:18.300
It's not quite half, but it's close.

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:20.840
They edited the whole
show on Final Cut 4.1,

00:18:20.930 --> 00:18:25.130
so it is possible to use
this workflow in 4.1.

00:18:25.140 --> 00:18:29.650
Right now, we are on 4.5 or Final Cut HD,
so that's where we -- this

00:18:29.860 --> 00:18:31.070
was a couple months back.

