00:23:09.260 --> 00:23:13.190
So, in terms of a workflow,
it was very streamlined.

00:23:13.190 --> 00:23:16.150
They had to hardly ever make tapes.

00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:18.300
When they needed to make a tape,
it was quite easy.

00:23:18.300 --> 00:23:21.660
They dumped, in this case,
they dumped their media to,

00:23:21.750 --> 00:23:24.470
they bought no extra hardware,
by the way.

00:23:24.470 --> 00:23:27.360
They just used a Dual G5
and a cinema display.

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:28.500
They had no extra hardware.

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:33.320
They did have an XR braid,
but they had no video cards, no nothing.

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:36.370
So, in order to make tapes,
what they did was they took

00:23:36.370 --> 00:23:40.100
the photo JPEG sequence,
dumped it into a DV sequence.

00:23:40.150 --> 00:23:44.680
It resized automatically
as a letterbox image.

00:23:44.700 --> 00:23:46.540
They did a render.

00:23:46.540 --> 00:23:51.880
It was less than,
actually more than real-time render.

00:23:51.880 --> 00:23:56.780
And with Final Cut 4,
when you play out a 2398 sequence,

00:23:56.780 --> 00:24:02.260
it adds in the 3-2 again as necessary
to go out to tape when you're DV.

00:24:02.260 --> 00:24:03.480
So, they were able to make.

00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:05.500
So, they were able to make cassettes
for their sound editors,

00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:08.530
for their negative cutters,
all that quite easily.

00:24:08.540 --> 00:24:10.000
So.

00:24:12.010 --> 00:24:14.880
So, in terms of this workflow,
how could we make it better?

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:17.920
Well, one thing that's really nice
and makes it better is with the

00:24:17.920 --> 00:24:22.800
introduction of Final Cut Pro HD,
we have access now to DVC Pro HD.

00:24:24.040 --> 00:24:30.140
And DVC Pro HD is really revolutionary
in terms of how we work with HD.

00:24:30.140 --> 00:24:35.220
It's the same impact as
DV had four or five years ago,

00:24:35.320 --> 00:24:36.530
six years ago.

00:24:37.090 --> 00:24:41.720
Because before DV was introduced,
editing video was really hard.

00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:46.100
And you would always have
kind of so-so quality.

00:24:46.100 --> 00:24:50.580
You would have a little capture card
with RCA inputs and you'd capture it in,

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:53.600
you'd get your little QuickTime movie,
and it would be really hard to edit.

00:24:53.620 --> 00:24:55.320
And DVC Pro HD was low-res and all that.

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:57.750
Then DV came along, you had FireWire,
you were able to plug

00:24:57.910 --> 00:25:00.090
that into your computer,
you didn't need a video card,

00:25:00.230 --> 00:25:01.250
anything like that.

00:25:01.290 --> 00:25:05.130
And you could edit in either iMovie,
Final Cut Pro, Final Cut Express.

00:25:05.140 --> 00:25:08.080
And that changed a lot of things.

00:25:08.170 --> 00:25:13.050
You had now something that looked
pretty much like Beta SP quality,

00:25:13.050 --> 00:25:16.530
which had been a
professional video product.

00:25:16.530 --> 00:25:18.720
And you had easy accessibility to it.

00:25:18.850 --> 00:25:22.210
You could have it on your
internal IDE drives and all that.

00:25:22.260 --> 00:25:22.260
So, with DVC Pro HD,
you had a lot of things

00:25:22.260 --> 00:25:22.260
that you could do.

00:25:22.260 --> 00:25:22.280
You could have it on your
internal IDE drives and all that.

00:25:22.290 --> 00:25:22.300
With DVC Pro HD, you had a lot of things
that you could do.

00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:22.330
You could have it on your
internal IDE drives and all that.

00:25:22.770 --> 00:25:27.100
With DVC Pro HD, you have the same thing.

00:25:27.160 --> 00:25:33.360
DVC Pro HD allows you to edit in true HD.

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:36.700
This is not half-resolution HD,
it's true HD.

00:25:36.700 --> 00:25:42.890
But you don't have to get hit with
the uncompressed HD data rate.

00:25:42.940 --> 00:25:49.700
So basically, with 24p DVC Pro HD,
it runs at 5.8 megabytes a second.

00:25:50.260 --> 00:25:55.320
As compared to the uncompressed,
10-bit uncompressed, which runs at 126.

00:25:55.420 --> 00:25:59.110
So you see a massive data
rate difference between the

00:25:59.110 --> 00:26:01.400
uncompressed and the DVC Pro HD.

00:26:01.400 --> 00:26:06.960
The reason for that is the DVC Pro HD is
the same format as the camera,

00:26:06.960 --> 00:26:09.490
the DVC Pro HD camera writes to tape.

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:16.330
And the heads on the DVC Pro HD camera
can't write 126 megabytes a second.

00:26:16.340 --> 00:26:19.500
So they had to find a way to
kind of shoehorn it down to a

00:26:19.610 --> 00:26:22.240
more manageable... data rate.

00:26:22.300 --> 00:26:27.600
So in their normal state,
you have this DV100,

00:26:27.600 --> 00:26:29.150
where it's 100 megabits.

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:31.580
That's with the small B, not the big B.

00:26:31.750 --> 00:26:32.260
Megabits.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:36.830
And of that,
we then only take 24 frames of it.

00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:38.080
It's set for 60.

00:26:38.080 --> 00:26:39.390
We take 24.

00:26:41.140 --> 00:26:48.800
So the other 36 frames get lopped off,
so we save that data rate.

00:26:48.800 --> 00:26:48.800
So,

00:26:48.850 --> 00:26:53.210
If you take a look at the chart
of the differences between HD,

00:26:53.210 --> 00:27:01.020
you take a look at the DVC Pro HD at 24p,
it is only slightly more than DV is.

00:27:02.030 --> 00:27:05.740
Now,
for an offline format to traditionalists,

00:27:05.820 --> 00:27:10.440
having an offline format that's
5.8 megabytes is still high.

00:27:10.480 --> 00:27:13.530
Okay, that's granted because you
are going to use still quite

00:27:13.530 --> 00:27:14.920
a bit of hard drive space.

00:27:14.980 --> 00:27:17.820
But the advantages are so great.

00:27:17.860 --> 00:27:22.750
You're now editing in complete HD res.

00:27:22.820 --> 00:27:25.580
This is not some fake HD.

00:27:25.580 --> 00:27:26.400
It's real HD.

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:27.850
You have real-time effects.

00:27:27.900 --> 00:27:32.520
You have HD playback through a
cinema display or DVI projector.

00:27:32.520 --> 00:27:37.800
Okay,
which if you go back to the computer too.

