00:31:45.280 --> 00:31:47.740
I'm sure, uh, were conversions.

00:31:47.850 --> 00:31:52.710
They weren't done, you know,
from frame one to the end credits

00:31:52.980 --> 00:31:54.390
as a digital intermediate.

00:31:54.400 --> 00:31:58.400
They're conversions of other pictures
that are finished ahead of time.

00:31:58.510 --> 00:32:01.470
So this is pretty cool because
this is the first time that,

00:32:01.530 --> 00:32:05.320
you know,
something this large has been put

00:32:05.470 --> 00:32:08.230
through this kind of pipeline.

00:32:09.990 --> 00:32:12.890
So let's talk about the
workflow a little bit.

00:32:12.970 --> 00:32:17.000
All the film was scanned by Imagica.

00:32:17.210 --> 00:32:21.520
Imagica was a large format
film service bureau.

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:26.490
Each frame was 4096 by 312 resolution.

00:32:26.500 --> 00:32:27.600
We just call it 4K.

00:32:27.600 --> 00:32:31.900
Each frame is a 10-bit Cineon log file.

00:32:33.020 --> 00:32:35.780
For those of you that
don't know what Cineon is,

00:32:35.780 --> 00:32:42.130
Cineon is a format that Kodak developed
that basically describes the gamut,

00:32:42.410 --> 00:32:48.230
which is the luminance,
the color range of a piece

00:32:48.390 --> 00:32:53.730
of motion picture negative.

00:32:53.900 --> 00:33:08.800
[Transcript missing]

00:33:09.260 --> 00:33:14.270
So you can imagine by the end,
I think for a portion of the show,

00:33:14.270 --> 00:33:17.990
there was about three
terabytes worth of data.

00:33:18.480 --> 00:33:20.900
Get that data in,
we database the scans so

00:33:20.900 --> 00:33:23.960
we know where they are,
where they came from, you know,

00:33:23.960 --> 00:33:27.400
what the lengths of the shots are,
which is really important.

00:33:27.400 --> 00:33:29.400
And now here's the interesting part.

00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:34.980
So we took those really huge files,
I mean obviously you've got a throughput

00:33:34.980 --> 00:33:37.400
issue when each frame is 50 megabytes.

00:33:37.400 --> 00:33:41.380
And what we did is convert
them to 8-bit log QuickTime.

00:33:41.380 --> 00:33:46.740
So there is a logarithmic
conversion of the 10-bit Cineons

00:33:46.740 --> 00:33:49.400
to QuickTime file format.

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:53.390
Obviously QuickTime file format gives
us the ability to scrub through images,

00:33:53.450 --> 00:34:00.400
we can output proxies,
get things reviewed fairly quickly,

00:34:00.500 --> 00:34:03.890
as opposed to, you know,
a sequence of Cineon frames which you

00:34:03.890 --> 00:34:06.400
can't really scrub through very easily.

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:09.590
easily.

00:34:10.020 --> 00:34:14.120
Then we had to look at the frames
and clean them and de-grain them.

00:34:14.120 --> 00:34:15.540
We'll get into that a little bit better.

00:34:15.540 --> 00:34:19.830
And then we had to examine the
shots to see if the pipeline that

00:34:19.840 --> 00:34:24.590
we're putting them through was
actually going to benefit the shots.

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:30.310
And in all but four cases,
we were using QuickTime movies.

00:34:30.340 --> 00:34:31.900
So imagine that.

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:37.360
We're going from a file format,
the QuickTime movie standard.

00:34:37.980 --> 00:34:42.000
It's traditionally used in video or
even high def to something that's much,

00:34:42.040 --> 00:34:42.720
much bigger.

00:34:42.780 --> 00:34:50.190
Something that's projected on a 70
by 100 foot screen without artifacts.

00:34:50.250 --> 00:35:03.760
And we're able to do that with
QuickTime because we've used

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:03.760
it for other feature films.

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:03.760
We know we're used to working with it.

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:03.760
We know how to get the
best results of it.

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:03.760
So the QuickTime movie
is basically a very good

00:35:04.430 --> 00:35:08.720
Sub-sample of those Cineon files.

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:12.910
It's the best of those 10 bits,
now an 8-bit.

00:35:13.790 --> 00:35:16.120
After examining it,
then we had to do color

00:35:16.120 --> 00:35:17.450
grade and effects.

00:35:17.450 --> 00:35:18.620
We'll get into that a little bit more.

00:35:18.620 --> 00:35:23.290
We'd render to FireWire drives,
and FireWire drives would get

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:28.010
shuttled off by hand to CFI,
which is the film recording lab,

00:35:28.010 --> 00:35:30.420
and it's now part of Technicolor.

00:35:30.420 --> 00:35:33.390
And we'd get those back and
project them in dailies.

00:35:33.420 --> 00:35:35.710
The dailies would go to an IMAX theater.

00:35:35.780 --> 00:35:38.520
You've got to see an
IMAX movie in an IMAX theater,

00:35:38.520 --> 00:35:40.250
see what it looks like.

00:35:41.460 --> 00:35:46.220
And before we really
got into doing takes,

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:50.130
or final shots, we did some tests.

00:35:50.270 --> 00:35:53.830
So we would do Cineon
versus QuickTime tests,

00:35:53.840 --> 00:35:57.840
and we would compare what
we were doing to the motion

00:35:57.840 --> 00:36:00.620
picture to the original scans.

00:36:00.620 --> 00:36:04.380
And we knew right away we
were on the right track.

00:36:04.380 --> 00:36:07.010
Everything was looking really great.

00:36:09.230 --> 00:36:13.040
So, there are a lot of challenges
from doing a giant screen picture.

00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:15.090
Obviously,
you're dealing with throughput,

00:36:15.200 --> 00:36:20.700
you're dealing with file sizes,
you're dealing with labs, possibly,

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:23.020
that aren't used to
working with QuickTime.

00:36:23.140 --> 00:36:29.490
We have to do color grading,
and color grading is more than, you know,

00:36:29.490 --> 00:36:33.090
the tint knob on your television set.

00:36:33.090 --> 00:36:33.090
Color grading is...

00:36:33.700 --> 00:36:37.320
Fixing the shots,
if the shots need to be fixed,

00:36:37.340 --> 00:36:44.010
and then creating a look for those shots
that makes it look warm or cool or has

00:36:44.130 --> 00:36:47.060
something to do with telling the story,
time of day kind of things.

00:36:47.060 --> 00:36:50.690
Then we added a lot of visual effects,
believe it or not,

00:36:50.700 --> 00:36:53.400
and we'll get into the technology too.

00:36:55.090 --> 00:36:59.900
So, challenges on this particular motion
picture is the director didn't know

00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:01.700
it was going to be an IMAX feature.

00:37:01.710 --> 00:37:04.070
He thought it might be an IMAX feature.

00:37:04.070 --> 00:37:11.540
And then he started shooting 70mm,
which is the traditional format for IMAX.

00:37:11.590 --> 00:37:15.160
And then realized, man,
these cameras are heavy,

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:18.930
these cameras are loud,
and I can't go within

00:37:18.930 --> 00:37:21.300
20 feet of the lions.

00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:24.090
with a 70 millimeter
camera because it just,

00:37:24.260 --> 00:37:25.360
they don't like it.

00:37:25.390 --> 00:37:26.690
They will move away.

00:37:26.950 --> 00:37:30.640
So he ended up shooting, oh, 75,
80% of the motion

00:37:30.640 --> 00:37:32.630
picture in 35 millimeter.

00:37:32.630 --> 00:37:34.720
So there's a problem right there.

00:37:34.720 --> 00:37:38.960
How do we get the 35 millimeter
to look like the 70 millimeter?

00:37:38.960 --> 00:37:41.210
Because it's going to end up in IMAX.

00:37:41.250 --> 00:37:43.870
He also shot with different film stocks.

00:37:44.010 --> 00:37:45.790
Don't ask me what they were.

00:37:45.900 --> 00:37:48.850
He doesn't know and we
couldn't figure it out.

00:37:49.010 --> 00:37:54.880
So we had to kind of balance things
and make things come to a center.

00:37:54.880 --> 00:38:00.980
And then we have to conform a motion
picture that was not necessarily shot

00:38:00.980 --> 00:38:04.560
for an IMAX screen to the IMAX specs.

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:08.670
And then because of
the filming conditions,

00:38:08.770 --> 00:38:15.900
a lot of what he did was he'd be shooting
in the middle of the day in the summer.

00:38:15.900 --> 00:38:19.240
Summer in Kalahari can
get up to 150 degrees.

00:38:20.120 --> 00:38:23.590
and he'd have his film
sitting in a cooler,

00:38:23.590 --> 00:38:24.820
basically.

00:38:24.950 --> 00:38:26.900
And he just grabbed
whatever he could get.

00:38:26.900 --> 00:38:29.900
And if he was running out of films,
the PA would go get some more film,

00:38:29.900 --> 00:38:31.680
who knows what it was,
and stick it in there.

00:38:31.680 --> 00:38:33.900
So he's not shooting in
the best of conditions.

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:37.840
So there's a few cases where we
had to do some restoration work

00:38:37.840 --> 00:38:43.170
because the film had been damaged or,
you know, the three layers, the red,

00:38:43.430 --> 00:38:48.440
green, blue layer of the emulsion was
actually starting to separate.

00:38:48.440 --> 00:38:51.220
Fortunately, that didn't happen too much.

00:38:51.460 --> 00:38:53.410
So let's get into the challenges.

00:38:53.450 --> 00:38:56.430
35 millimeter film is four perforations.

00:38:56.470 --> 00:39:00.840
Runs up and down through the projector.

00:39:01.050 --> 00:39:05.980
And let's say that's
a 35 millimeter still.

00:39:08.090 --> 00:39:09.890
"Seventy.

00:39:10.350 --> 00:39:11.980
That's a big difference.

00:39:12.050 --> 00:39:15.290
In fact, I like that a lot.

00:39:15.290 --> 00:39:15.290
Let's go back.

00:39:16.090 --> 00:39:21.310
That's 16 times the
area of 35 millimeter.

00:39:21.620 --> 00:39:27.230
That is a 50 megabyte frame
versus a 5 megabyte frame.

00:39:27.240 --> 00:39:30.240
Four to five is usually what 2K is.

00:39:30.240 --> 00:39:33.270
And we have to make...

00:39:34.830 --> 00:39:36.560
Look like that.

00:39:36.560 --> 00:39:37.470
That's a big challenge.

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:40.110
So how do we do something like that?

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:43.250
First of all,
we have to reduce the 35mm grain.

00:39:43.250 --> 00:39:46.250
We have to identify what's
grain versus texture.

00:39:46.390 --> 00:39:51.200
We don't want to get rid of grain and
all of a sudden the lion's coats or

00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:53.700
the antelope's coats just disappear.

00:39:53.920 --> 00:39:55.840
They don't want it to
look like solid browns.

00:39:55.840 --> 00:39:57.700
You still have to have some texture.

00:39:57.700 --> 00:39:59.670
Then you also have to
preserve edge detail,

00:39:59.710 --> 00:40:01.700
which is the real trick.

00:40:01.700 --> 00:40:05.840
Because if you can determine
what the edges are,

00:40:05.900 --> 00:40:11.090
then you're preserving that
resolution of the image versus

00:40:11.090 --> 00:40:16.650
noise or grain in this example.

00:40:17.350 --> 00:40:24.900
So here's an image cut in very,
very close of one of the shots.

00:40:24.900 --> 00:40:26.740
You can see the grain.

00:40:26.740 --> 00:40:29.390
You can see the red, green, blue.

00:40:29.650 --> 00:40:32.110
And believe it or not,
this has been color

00:40:32.110 --> 00:40:35.130
corrected as a first step.

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:41.190
And what we had to do is, you know,
determine what the antlers are,

00:40:41.200 --> 00:40:45.140
the antelope, clear up that sky because
we've got a solid sky.

00:40:45.140 --> 00:40:46.440
I mean,
you're really going to see the grain.

00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:49.590
And this is what we ended up with.

00:40:50.980 --> 00:40:52.440
It's a much cleaner picture.

00:40:52.440 --> 00:40:53.900
You can see edge detail.

00:40:53.900 --> 00:40:56.150
You can see that there
are antelope there.

00:40:56.210 --> 00:41:01.150
This one actually has been color
corrected and color graded.

00:41:01.220 --> 00:41:04.330
The difference between
color correction is,

00:41:04.480 --> 00:41:08.200
in this example,
if we got film that was sort of blue,

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:13.490
because he would shoot without a
color correction filter on the camera.

00:41:13.660 --> 00:41:16.230
We have to bring it to gray.

00:41:16.240 --> 00:41:18.600
We have to create what's
called a gray balance look.

00:41:18.600 --> 00:41:21.570
That's important because now
we show it to the director

00:41:21.570 --> 00:41:24.600
and the producers and say,
"Okay, this is what you shot.

00:41:24.600 --> 00:41:27.980
This is what you saw when you
were on location." They say,

00:41:27.980 --> 00:41:30.570
"Yes, it is." Then you color
grade it as a second step.

00:41:30.600 --> 00:41:35.120
Color grading it is basically, "Well,
we want it to help you tell the

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:39.590
story." It doesn't look like Mutual
of Omaha's Wild Kingdom necessarily.

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:44.120
We want it to look like a feature film
so everything is sweetened a little bit.

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:47.400
Conforming is another issue.

00:41:47.400 --> 00:41:51.330
This is what's called a sacred master.

00:41:51.330 --> 00:41:55.550
A sacred master basically says,
"This is the area you've got

00:41:55.560 --> 00:41:57.750
to play with in your film."

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.570
So if you look at this,
this is a field chart.

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:02.340
There's two things.

00:42:02.340 --> 00:42:07.750
That area in the red is credit safe.

00:42:08.170 --> 00:42:11.220
So if you imagine going to a movie,
like Next Door,

00:42:11.220 --> 00:42:14.900
and you watch the credits,
they're going up and down or dissolving,

00:42:14.900 --> 00:42:15.760
they're filling the frame.

00:42:15.760 --> 00:42:17.640
You can't do that with an IMAX picture.

00:42:17.640 --> 00:42:23.450
Because where that plus sign is,
is the viewing center of viewing.

00:42:23.450 --> 00:42:26.430
It's not the middle,
it's the center of viewing.

00:42:26.440 --> 00:42:28.620
So the center of viewing
in an IMAX picture is about

00:42:28.660 --> 00:42:29.630
a third of the way up.

00:42:29.630 --> 00:42:31.580
So that's where your eyes are looking.

00:42:31.580 --> 00:42:34.310
And you've got all this extra
space over your head that just

00:42:34.310 --> 00:42:36.080
makes you feel like you're there.

00:42:36.080 --> 00:42:37.700
It just sort of surrounds you.

00:42:37.700 --> 00:42:40.220
But where the audience is looking,
it's about a third of the way up.

00:42:40.290 --> 00:42:43.340
So credits obviously can't
go all the way to the top.

00:42:43.360 --> 00:42:46.660
So we're looking for that
sweet spot in the center.

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:49.750
Like I said before,
he's not necessarily shooting for that.

00:42:49.780 --> 00:42:53.710
He's not necessarily framing
all of the lions or whatever the

00:42:53.710 --> 00:42:55.890
action is for that sweet spot.

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:05.820
So, the center of interest in a picture,
on an iMac or large format picture is

00:43:05.910 --> 00:43:07.590
not necessarily the center of the frame.

00:43:07.600 --> 00:43:08.320
So what do we do?

00:43:08.530 --> 00:43:15.210
Here's a couple of examples where on the
left we have the guinea hens and their

00:43:15.550 --> 00:43:19.340
focus spot is actually about halfway up.

00:43:19.400 --> 00:43:24.720
And on this shot, this helicopter shot,
obviously the center of

00:43:24.720 --> 00:43:27.270
interest is way up at the top.

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:30.720
So what do we do?

00:43:30.730 --> 00:43:30.730
We switch to demo.

00:43:39.750 --> 00:43:43.830
So for the guineas,
we have to lower the shot in the frame,

00:43:43.830 --> 00:43:46.100
and here's where the effects come in.

00:43:46.100 --> 00:43:49.040
We create a digital extension.

00:43:49.080 --> 00:43:51.310
We have to do that a lot.

00:43:53.180 --> 00:43:55.100
Same thing for the helicopter shot.

00:43:55.100 --> 00:44:01.860
In this case,
we're completely replacing the sky.

00:44:05.250 --> 00:44:07.100
Everything has to be tracked.

00:44:07.100 --> 00:44:11.800
So it becomes not just a reframing
issue or a composition issue,

00:44:11.800 --> 00:44:14.400
it becomes a full-blown effect.

00:44:20.310 --> 00:44:29.050
Restoration,
we have a lot of dirt and scratches.

00:44:29.050 --> 00:44:29.050
I think you can see a
little bit up there.

00:44:29.050 --> 00:44:29.050
I'll go ahead and play the movie.

00:44:32.680 --> 00:44:34.200
This is a pretty good example.

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:38.100
Again, this is just a little part of it,
a little part of that image.

00:44:38.100 --> 00:44:39.360
This is much, much bigger.

00:44:39.360 --> 00:44:43.440
It's probably eight times larger than
the part that I'm showing you right now.

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:46.040
Like I said, you have dust and scratches.

00:44:46.090 --> 00:44:48.950
You've got the emulsion
starting to separate.

00:44:48.950 --> 00:44:51.030
We have to correct all of that.

00:44:51.040 --> 00:44:54.620
This is part of the digital
intermediate process.

00:44:54.620 --> 00:44:55.880
We're just not coloring it.

00:44:55.990 --> 00:44:57.180
We're just not correcting it.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:45:00.210
We're making the frames as
perfect as possible because

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:02.220
that's what you're going to see.

00:45:02.220 --> 00:45:04.090
It's not happening in any other place.

00:45:04.090 --> 00:45:08.790
It's happening in the computers and it's
happening to fix these kinds of things.

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:13.750
Just for fun,
when we had the wrap party for the crew,

00:45:13.780 --> 00:45:18.950
I had a little contest to see
who could figure out how many

00:45:18.950 --> 00:45:21.870
pieces of dirt got cleaned.

00:45:23.200 --> 00:45:27.020
We had a little gift
bag of stuff like that.

00:45:27.020 --> 00:45:31.580
The software actually keeps track of
that because I'm sort of masochistic.

00:45:31.580 --> 00:45:35.420
I wanted to know how much pieces
of dirt that we cleaned up.

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:39.740
We cleaned up 583,000 pieces of dirt.

00:45:39.740 --> 00:45:46.080
Some of that, let's say 100,000,
was removed procedurally.

00:45:46.080 --> 00:45:49.470
Procedurally basically means
we had a computer analyze

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:51.360
the image and sort of fix it.

00:45:52.160 --> 00:45:55.060
It's not that simple,
but that's what we did.

00:45:55.060 --> 00:45:58.140
The rest of it had to be done by hand.

00:45:58.550 --> 00:46:03.150
Over 400,000 pieces of dirt
had to be done by hand.

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:04.560
And here's the reason for it.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:05.840
Why isn't there software?

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:07.980
Yeah, there's some software,
but it doesn't work

00:46:08.080 --> 00:46:09.570
like the human eye does.

00:46:09.570 --> 00:46:11.100
It'll make mistakes.

00:46:11.140 --> 00:46:15.360
And if you make a mistake at 4K,
it's pretty obvious that your mistakes

00:46:15.720 --> 00:46:18.280
are getting magnified pretty largely.

00:46:20.120 --> 00:46:22.350
And there's also dust in the shot.

00:46:22.390 --> 00:46:27.540
There's also heat waves, there's mirages,
there's distortions going on.

00:46:27.540 --> 00:46:31.530
So you have to use your eye
to get rid of that stuff.

00:46:31.530 --> 00:46:35.730
And that was the major
production part for us.

00:46:35.780 --> 00:46:37.080
Can we go back to the other?

00:46:50.250 --> 00:46:51.200
Color grading.

00:46:51.200 --> 00:46:51.770
Okay.

00:46:51.900 --> 00:46:54.350
Part of color grading,
I put stabilizing in there because

00:46:54.410 --> 00:46:55.650
I'm not sure where else to put it.

00:46:55.750 --> 00:46:59.860
He's shooting on location
in difficult situations.

00:46:59.860 --> 00:47:03.150
Not every time is the camera locked
down and also you've got heat

00:47:03.200 --> 00:47:05.240
distortion going on in the image.

00:47:05.240 --> 00:47:07.250
So the image is moving around a lot.

00:47:07.260 --> 00:47:10.010
If he's flying in a helicopter,
the camera's strapped

00:47:10.100 --> 00:47:11.880
underneath it with bungee cords.

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:15.110
Sometimes the bungee cords aren't
tight enough and you get some

00:47:15.110 --> 00:47:16.900
jitter going on in the frame.

00:47:16.900 --> 00:47:21.520
So that has to be stabilized
because you want to want the shots

00:47:21.520 --> 00:47:24.720
to look as perfect as possible.

00:47:24.720 --> 00:47:28.100
Color correcting, like I said,
