00:59:29.320 --> 00:59:46.510
Standards 3D Color Lookup Tables.

00:59:46.510 --> 00:59:46.510
What's a 3D Color Lookup Table?

00:59:46.510 --> 00:59:46.510
A Color Lookup Table basically says,
"Alright,

00:59:46.510 --> 00:59:46.510
this is the amount of colors you can use
to display an image." There's software,

00:59:46.510 --> 00:59:46.510
there's hardware lookup tables.

00:59:46.510 --> 00:59:46.510
A 3D Color Lookup Table

00:59:46.750 --> 00:59:49.800
is saying that all the
values are interrelated,

00:59:49.840 --> 00:59:52.030
and that's how film works.

00:59:52.070 --> 00:59:55.360
I mean, getting it to a high-depth
finishing station is great,

00:59:55.360 --> 00:59:59.320
but if you really want to work with
the data the way that film works,

00:59:59.340 --> 01:00:01.730
you have to work with a 3D lookup table.

01:00:01.890 --> 01:00:05.980
And it just means the red, green,
blue affect each other.

01:00:05.980 --> 01:00:08.900
If you affect the brightness of red,
you're

01:00:09.330 --> 01:00:12.990
In a film 3D lookup table,
something's happening to

01:00:12.990 --> 01:00:18.100
green and blue because that's
how the film emulsion works.

01:00:18.100 --> 01:00:22.090
Kodak has created a 3D
lookup table fairly recently,

01:00:22.140 --> 01:00:25.300
but it's only available for Kodak stocks.

01:00:25.300 --> 01:00:33.510
So there's no 3D lookup table that
I know of for Fuji or other film stocks.

01:00:34.120 --> 01:00:36.840
Also, because it's new,
it's not a standard.

01:00:36.840 --> 01:00:40.910
It's being adopted for a lot
of color grading systems yet.

01:00:41.130 --> 01:00:45.610
And then you're faced with the
arcane chemical technology,

01:00:45.770 --> 01:00:47.040
which is how I started.

01:00:47.040 --> 01:00:49.800
I started off in an optical lab.

01:00:49.940 --> 01:00:53.540
I know about optical printers and
keeping the right temperature of

01:00:53.540 --> 01:00:55.340
film suits and all that stuff.

01:00:55.490 --> 01:01:02.990
And there are no direct correlations
between traditional color correcting

01:01:02.990 --> 01:01:07.460
methods and film to digital.

01:01:08.120 --> 01:01:11.170
Now, some software will say
we have printer lights,

01:01:11.250 --> 01:01:13.570
we can match what's going on in the lab.

01:01:13.570 --> 01:01:17.150
That's not necessarily true because
traditional color correction,

01:01:17.170 --> 01:01:21.600
if you say you're adding 10 points
of red or adding some red to it,

01:01:21.640 --> 01:01:23.800
you're not cranking the red.

01:01:23.800 --> 01:01:25.860
That's not how film works.

01:01:26.840 --> 01:01:30.220
But in most,
the software that's available now,

01:01:30.230 --> 01:01:33.270
you say, well,
the DP wants you to add red.

01:01:33.280 --> 01:01:34.480
Well, you add red to it.

01:01:34.580 --> 01:01:35.540
That's not correct.

01:01:35.560 --> 01:01:36.860
That's not how film works.

01:01:36.930 --> 01:01:38.560
You're overdriving the image.

01:01:40.660 --> 01:01:42.830
You know, traditionally in a DP,
you'll say, I want more red,

01:01:42.840 --> 01:01:45.460
I want you to add some neutral density,
I want you to do this or that,

01:01:45.460 --> 01:01:49.880
and you can add a list of
criteria for his recipe,

01:01:49.880 --> 01:01:53.030
and still the film will hold up,
it'll still look good.

01:01:53.040 --> 01:01:57.420
But digitally,
you can seriously overdrive the image.

01:01:57.420 --> 01:02:02.120
If the look that's being
required is pretty severe,

01:02:02.200 --> 01:02:05.020
you can overdrive the image.

